│ Understanding the Issue: The problem is that the transformation from a      │
│ select instruction with icmp condition to uadd.sat intrinsic introduces     │
│ more poison than the original code. In the source, when the add operands    │
│ contain poison but the condition is true, the select returns the true value │
│ (-1). However, the uadd.sat intrinsic returns poison whenever any input is  │
│ poison, making the target more poisonous than the source.\n\n2. Analyzing   │
│ `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the transformation occurs in                │
│ `canonicalizeSaturatedAdd` function, specifically matching the pattern `(~X │
│ u< Y) ? -1 : (X + Y)` → `uadd.sat(X, Y)`. The debug output confirms that    │
│ the second element of the result changes from -1 in the source to poison in │
│ the target.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The root cause is in the pattern     │
│ matching within `canonicalizeSaturatedAdd`. The function uses               │
│ `m_Not(m_Value(X))` which matches xor operations with all-ones constants,   │
│ but `m_AllOnes()` (used internally by `m_Not`) allows poison in vector      │
│ elements. When the all-ones constant contains poison (like `<i32 -1, i32    │
│ poison>`), the transformation becomes invalid because the poison behavior   │
│ differs between the select and uadd.sat.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n    │
│ + Line 1049: Change `match(Cmp0, m_Not(m_Value(X)))` to `match(Cmp0,        │
│ m_NotForbidPoison(m_Value(X)))`\n   + Line 1059: Change `match(FVal,        │
│ m_c_Add(m_Not(m_Specific(X)), m_Specific(Y)))` to `match(FVal,              │
│ m_c_Add(m_NotForbidPoison(m_Specific(X)), m_Specific(Y)))`\n   \n   These   │
│ changes ensure that the transformation only applies when the \"not\"        │
│ operation doesn't involve poison in the constant, preserving the            │
│ equivalence between the original select and the uadd.sat intrinsic.\n\n5.   │
│ Conclusion: By using `m_NotForbidPoison` instead of `m_Not`, we prevent the │
│ transformation when the all-ones constant contains poison, which maintains  │
│ the correct poison semantics. This fix ensures that the optimization is     │
│ only applied when it's safe to do so, avoiding the introduction of          │
│ additional poison that would make the target more poisonous than the        │
│ source."})                                                                  │
